fields.description:
Consider a Makefile with 
all: main
main: main.c
clean: 
      rm -f main
as its content.

Which of the following is correct if the following code is executed. 
make
touch clean
make clean

Write a function "find_alpha" which will take a SET of any set of values and find all the non alphabetic characters and return the non alphabetic characters as a SET.

For Example 
>>> find_non_alpha({'a', 'b', ',', '.'})
>>> {',', '.'}
>>> find_non_alpha({'a', '#', '12', '@', '3'})
>>> {'#', '12', '@', '3'}
Note:- Answer to this question will be required in an another question. Please copy the final answer before submitting.

write a function "sort_list" which will take a list of tuples where each tuple will have two elements first element is a alphabetic character and second element is the no of occurrences of that character.

Sort the list from highest occurrences to lowest occurrences and return list of tuples.

If the characters has same no of occurrences then sort the list by alphabetical order.

For Example: 
>>> sort_list([("b", 2), ("a", 2)])
>>> [("a", 2), ("b", 2)]
>>> sort_list([("c", 2), ("d", 3)])
>>> [("d", 3), ("c", 2)]

write a function "remove_non_alpha" which will take a string and then perform following operation on string :-
  • Remove all the non alphabetic characters.
  • Count the no of occurrences of a character.
  • Sort the count of occurrences from highest to lowest.
  • If the characters has same no of occurrences then sort the list by alphabetical order.

    Function should return list of tuples where first element of tuple is the character and second element is no of occurrences of the character.

    For Example: 
    >>> remove_non_alpha("ab#c")
>>>  [("a", 1), ("b", 1), ("c", 1)]
>>> remove_non_alpha("123a")
>>>  [("a", 1)]
    You can use the functions from previous questions to get non alphabetic character.

What is wrong with this code (assuming it is run in some empty directory)? 

# clean_tex.py
import os
def cleanup(tex_file_pth):
    base = os.path.splitext(tex_file_pth)[0]
    for ext in ('.aux', '.log'):
        f = base + ext
        if os.path.exists(f):
            os.remove(f)


# test_clean_tex.py
from unittest import mock

@mock.patch('os.remove')
def test_cleanup_removes_extra_files(mock_remove):
    cleanup('foo.tex')
    expected = [mock.call('foo.' + x) for x in ('aux', 'log')]
    mock_remove.assert_has_calls(expected)

  • For any programming questions, you can submit solutions as many times as you want without a penalty. You may skip questions and solve them later.
  • You may use your computer's Python/IPython shell or an editor to solve the problem and cut/paste the solution to the web interface.
  • You are not allowed to use any internet resources, i.e. no google etc.
  • Do not copy or share the questions or answers with anyone until the exam is complete for everyone.
  • All your attempts at the questions are logged. Do not try to outsmart and break the testing system. If you do, we know who you are and we will expel you from the course. You have been warned.

We hope you enjoy taking this exam !!!
